Adjust rack to middle position and preheat #oven{} to 400 degrees. Wash and dry all produce. Bring @chicken stock concentrate{4} and @water{7%cups} to a boil in a #medium pot{}. Once boiling, reduce heat to low. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{4}(trimmed and thinly sliced), separating whites from greens. Trim @button mushrooms{8%ounce}, then slice into about ¼-inch-thick pieces.

Heat a large drizzle of @olive oil{2%tablespoon} in a #large pan{} over medium heat. Add scallion whites and mushrooms and cook, stirring, until slightly softened, ~{1-2%minutes}. Add @arborio rice{1.5%cup} and cook, stirring, until translucent, ~{1-2%minutes}. Add stock, ½ cup at a time, stirring after each addition. Allow rice to absorb most of the stock before adding more. Continue until al dente and creamy, ~{30-35%minutes}.

Pat @chicken breasts{24%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}. Lay two slices of @prosciutto{4%ounce} beside each other on a flat surface. Tightly roll prosciutto around chicken. Repeat with another two slices of prosciutto and other chicken breast (you may have some prosciutto left over; use the rest as you like).

Heat a large drizzle of @vegetable oil{1%teaspoon} in another large pan over medium-high heat. Add wrapped chicken and sear until browned, about ~{2%minutes} per side. Transfer seared chicken to a lightly oiled #baking sheet{}. Place in oven and roast until chicken is cooked through, about ~{15%minutes}. Let rest a few minutes, then slice crosswise.

Quarter @lemon{2}. Stir @garlic herb butter{4%tablespoon}, half the @parmesan cheese{½%cup}, a squeeze of lemon juice, and any juices released by chicken into risotto. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, or more lemon juice (to taste).

Slice chicken crosswise. Divide risotto between plates. Sprinkle with scallion greens and remaining Parmesan. Top with chicken. Drizzle with @truffle oil{5%teaspoon} (to taste). Serve with any remaining lemon wedges on the side for squeezing over.

> We love a good, simple chicken breast. But to really elevate it, you've got to be creative with how you prepare it. In this recipe, our chefs took up that challenge, drawing inspiration from Italian saltimbocca. The meat is wrapped in slices of prosciutto, seared until it's delightfully crisp, and placed atop mushroom risotto with a drizzle of umami-rich truffle oil.